		<div class="comment_text"><p>As far as jobs go, another data point:<br><a href="http://disq.us/url?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.indeed.com%2Fjobtrends%3Fq%3Dcoldfusion%26l%3D%3AcGdf6XqRIQgPcepuxMTxiI68tRQ&amp;cuid=3321886" rel="nofollow noopener" title="http://www.indeed.com/jobtrends?q=coldfusion&amp;l=">http://www.indeed.com/jobtr...</a></p><p>But as Ray mentions - relying on only one core language is career suicide as a developer.</p><p>The CF market has matured and is declining. Although there are many companies that have invested millions into their application, and it's not something they'll get rid of any time soon. But it's a self-fueling problem in that as the # of jobs goes down, the talent pool naturally shrinks as people invest their learning elsewhere, which because it's hard to find people causes companies to work on migrations to other technologies thus further shrinking the # of jobs.</p><p>Being a JavaScript master is the strategy I'd recommend to a CF'er. It's something as a ColdFusion developer you can naturally add to your CF apps, as part of your regular job. While at the same time JavaScript is the #1 most sought after skill at the moment.</p><p>Try to only use CF as a back-end REST API, while building JavaScript heavy UIs using something like Angular, Ember, Ionic, etc... and you'll be in really good business (could even then swap out the CF part later as your JS app won't care as long as the interface remains the same).</p></div>
