		<div class="comment_text"><p>I think one other thing to consider is the state of application development, in general, and the way it has changed in the last few years. I feel like it used to be that you could just have ColdFusion and you could built a rock-solid application, even an enterprise one.</p><p>But, the expectation of applications has started to shift in huge ways. With single-page apps, mobile apps, WebSockets, image processing, telephony integration, etc., I feel like no "one" technology is sufficient any more. So, while we build stuff in ColdFusion, we also have stuff - in the same application ecosystem - written in other languages like Node.js.</p><p>For what it does well, I think ColdFusion is amazing. But, trying to get it to everything is painful, by no fault of its own. Things are just evolving. So, maybe a bit off-topic.</p></div>
